WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.579 --> 00:00:02.370
MATTHEW HENDERSHOT:
Good morning, everyone.

00:00:02.370 --> 00:00:03.490
Thanks for joining us today.

00:00:03.490 --> 00:00:04.740
My name is Matthew Hendershot.

00:00:04.740 --> 00:00:06.740
I am the video editor,
post-production guy

00:00:06.740 --> 00:00:08.900
for the Talks at Google team.

00:00:08.900 --> 00:00:11.400
And for the past year, I've
also served as a very personally

00:00:11.400 --> 00:00:15.340
satisfying role as director
for the original online series,

00:00:15.340 --> 00:00:16.420
"Songs of the Road."

00:00:16.420 --> 00:00:18.295
Joining me here today
to talk more about Song

00:00:18.295 --> 00:00:20.040
Craft presents and
"Songs of the Road"

00:00:20.040 --> 00:00:23.170
are the stars of the show,
Ben Arthur, singer/songwriter,

00:00:23.170 --> 00:00:26.226
radio host Rob Reinhart, and
producers Al Houghton and Mike

00:00:26.226 --> 00:00:26.726
Crehore.

00:00:30.949 --> 00:00:31.740
Good morning, guys.

00:00:31.740 --> 00:00:32.479
Good morning.

00:00:32.479 --> 00:00:33.490
What don't we go down
the line, and you

00:00:33.490 --> 00:00:35.550
guys can just personally
introduce yourself.

00:00:35.550 --> 00:00:37.470
Tell us a little bit
about your background

00:00:37.470 --> 00:00:39.800
and what your role
is with the show.

00:00:39.800 --> 00:00:41.180
BEN ARTHUR: Sure.

00:00:41.180 --> 00:00:41.950
My name's Ben.

00:00:41.950 --> 00:00:43.880
I do the songwriting.

00:00:43.880 --> 00:00:46.470
So we bring in an artist,
and I sit down with them,

00:00:46.470 --> 00:00:52.300
and write and record a song in
a very brief period of time.

00:00:52.300 --> 00:00:53.780
ROB REINHART: I'm Rob Reinhart.

00:00:53.780 --> 00:00:55.950
I host a syndicated
radio program

00:00:55.950 --> 00:00:57.640
called, "Acoustic Cafe."

00:00:57.640 --> 00:00:59.600
We're in our 21st year.

00:00:59.600 --> 00:01:03.260
And in this project,
I drove the car.

00:01:03.260 --> 00:01:04.910
I played the bald guy.

00:01:04.910 --> 00:01:07.740
Look at all this hair up here.

00:01:07.740 --> 00:01:09.990
BEN ARTHUR: Not that he's
self-conscious, or anything.

00:01:09.990 --> 00:01:10.820
ROB REINHART: And,
along the way,

00:01:10.820 --> 00:01:13.560
have done some interviews with
the artists that are involved

00:01:13.560 --> 00:01:16.570
in the Song Craft project.

00:01:16.570 --> 00:01:19.380
ALAN HOUGHTON: I'm Al
Houghton, musician, producer.

00:01:19.380 --> 00:01:22.100
I have a studio downtown
called Dubway Studios.

00:01:22.100 --> 00:01:25.190
And we're involved in
producing the music

00:01:25.190 --> 00:01:27.837
that the songwriters write.

00:01:27.837 --> 00:01:29.420
MICHAEL CREHORE: And
I'm Mike Crehore.

00:01:29.420 --> 00:01:31.770
I was partners with
Al at Dubway Studios.

00:01:31.770 --> 00:01:33.660
That's how we met up
with Ben originally.

00:01:33.660 --> 00:01:37.220
And helped to produce
the music, and capture it

00:01:37.220 --> 00:01:41.862
in whatever strange place where
we needed to capture it in, so.

00:01:41.862 --> 00:01:43.570
MATTHEW HENDERSHOT:
Now Rob, as you said,

00:01:43.570 --> 00:01:45.879
you've been doing Acoustic
Cafe for over 20 years.

00:01:45.879 --> 00:01:46.670
ROB REINHART: Yeah.

00:01:46.670 --> 00:01:49.044
MATTHEW HENDERSHOT: What
brought you into this situation,

00:01:49.044 --> 00:01:52.810
where you were starting back
over the brand-building process

00:01:52.810 --> 00:01:55.260
in a whole new medium--
that of online video--

00:01:55.260 --> 00:01:58.120
and with a whole
new group of people?

00:01:58.120 --> 00:01:58.940
ROB REINHART: Yeah.

00:01:58.940 --> 00:02:01.500
You know, actually,
it's interesting.

00:02:01.500 --> 00:02:05.900
I've been turning down video
options since the late '90s.

00:02:05.900 --> 00:02:07.550
People who have
come along and said,

00:02:07.550 --> 00:02:09.389
you really have stuff on video.

00:02:09.389 --> 00:02:12.346
This is probably 1997, '98.

00:02:12.346 --> 00:02:14.720
And the reason I wanted to
get involved with this project

00:02:14.720 --> 00:02:16.740
was it specifically
was not going

00:02:16.740 --> 00:02:18.532
to be the thing that
I wanted to avoid,

00:02:18.532 --> 00:02:24.640
which was yet another series
of guys and girls with guitars,

00:02:24.640 --> 00:02:27.000
in high definition,
playing their songs.

00:02:27.000 --> 00:02:28.690
I just thought,
you know, the web

00:02:28.690 --> 00:02:30.040
was sort of flooded with that.

00:02:30.040 --> 00:02:32.570
And I didn't see any
reason to contribute to it.

00:02:32.570 --> 00:02:34.630
I didn't see how it would
extend my brand any.

00:02:34.630 --> 00:02:36.130
What I was interested
in doing was

00:02:36.130 --> 00:02:38.240
something that had a
narrative, something

00:02:38.240 --> 00:02:40.550
that presented a new story.

00:02:40.550 --> 00:02:43.300
It wasn't just an
artist doing what

00:02:43.300 --> 00:02:46.080
they do on my radio
program, but with pictures.

00:02:46.080 --> 00:02:49.110
Instead, it actually
had a story to it.

00:02:49.110 --> 00:02:52.325
And so that's what was such an
attractive thing when Ben sort

00:02:52.325 --> 00:02:54.410
of threw this idea out there.

00:02:54.410 --> 00:02:57.260
It was an interesting
way to tell a new story.

00:02:57.260 --> 00:02:58.500
That's why.

00:02:58.500 --> 00:03:00.820
MATTHEW HENDERSHOT:
So this was about 2013

00:03:00.820 --> 00:03:03.980
when the conversation began for
us to start working together.

00:03:03.980 --> 00:03:07.450
But we had been doing
this narrative approach

00:03:07.450 --> 00:03:08.980
for quite a bit more than that.

00:03:08.980 --> 00:03:12.140
Ben, why don't you talk
about how the three of you,

00:03:12.140 --> 00:03:15.600
and then, ultimately, I got
involved in that, came about.

00:03:15.600 --> 00:03:17.360
BEN ARTHUR: Yeah, so
for a couple years

00:03:17.360 --> 00:03:20.370
we had been just
throwing artists together

00:03:20.370 --> 00:03:24.160
in the guys' studio
and writing songs

00:03:24.160 --> 00:03:27.350
with them-- John Wesley
Harding and Ximena Sarinana

00:03:27.350 --> 00:03:29.400
and a whole bunch
of other folks.

00:03:29.400 --> 00:03:35.220
And we needed to grow our
ability to distribute that

00:03:35.220 --> 00:03:37.460
and to bring in great artists.

00:03:37.460 --> 00:03:41.320
And Rob knows everyone.

00:03:41.320 --> 00:03:42.834
All of the artists.

00:03:42.834 --> 00:03:45.250
MATTHEW HENDERSHOT: From the
video standpoint, when we all

00:03:45.250 --> 00:03:47.340
got together and
started doing this,

00:03:47.340 --> 00:03:50.400
we wanted to tell it as
like a reality TV show.

00:03:50.400 --> 00:03:53.530
But we knew we were not
going to be on TV at first,

00:03:53.530 --> 00:03:56.465
so it was all about being
online, trying to find a way

00:03:56.465 --> 00:03:57.340
to publish it online.

00:03:57.340 --> 00:03:59.756
I think some of the first ones
we published in five parts.

00:03:59.756 --> 00:04:00.530
BEN ARTHUR: Yeah.

00:04:00.530 --> 00:04:02.080
MATTHEW HENDERSHOT: And so
we could keep the size down,

00:04:02.080 --> 00:04:04.040
and keep it contained as
something people would watch.

00:04:04.040 --> 00:04:06.400
And then, we also did it in
Dubway Studios, your studio

00:04:06.400 --> 00:04:07.240
downtown.

00:04:07.240 --> 00:04:10.400
So we had a little bit of a
contained studio space as well,

00:04:10.400 --> 00:04:10.922
right?

00:04:10.922 --> 00:04:12.630
Why don't you guys
talk about the process

00:04:12.630 --> 00:04:15.070
that we were going
through back then,

00:04:15.070 --> 00:04:17.800
and how it all came
together as a show.

00:04:17.800 --> 00:04:21.589
ALAN HOUGHTON: Well,
you know, initially it

00:04:21.589 --> 00:04:22.650
was pretty small minded.

00:04:22.650 --> 00:04:24.608
It was like, wow, how do
we get more, you know,

00:04:24.608 --> 00:04:27.080
studio hours in the studio?

00:04:27.080 --> 00:04:29.020
But then it became
obvious, this is actually

00:04:29.020 --> 00:04:31.260
way more interesting
and cool than that.

00:04:31.260 --> 00:04:35.740
So by putting songwriters who
don't know each other at all,

00:04:35.740 --> 00:04:38.160
there's a drama
element, automatically.

00:04:38.160 --> 00:04:40.614
And we did not know
how that would manifest

00:04:40.614 --> 00:04:41.780
or what would happen at all.

00:04:41.780 --> 00:04:43.860
In fact, we were thinking
almost more technically.

00:04:43.860 --> 00:04:45.776
You know, people'll be
interested in like what

00:04:45.776 --> 00:04:49.160
mike you use, and how you
use the software, and all

00:04:49.160 --> 00:04:49.900
this stuff.

00:04:49.900 --> 00:04:53.120
And as, as it evolved,
it became more apparent

00:04:53.120 --> 00:04:55.450
that actually the dynamic
of the songwriting

00:04:55.450 --> 00:04:58.540
is much more the cool story.

00:04:58.540 --> 00:05:01.230
And the other stuff became
less and less critical

00:05:01.230 --> 00:05:03.670
as we went on.

00:05:03.670 --> 00:05:06.540
MATTHEW HENDERSHOT: So
2013, South by Southwest,

00:05:06.540 --> 00:05:09.624
we decide to go down
and take a crack at it.

00:05:09.624 --> 00:05:10.290
How did that go?

00:05:12.796 --> 00:05:14.420
ROB REINHART: Well,
you know, actually,

00:05:14.420 --> 00:05:16.909
so you guys started in
'09 doing this at Dubway?

00:05:16.909 --> 00:05:18.200
BEN ARTHUR: Somewhere in there.

00:05:18.200 --> 00:05:20.700
ROB REINHART: Because it was
'09 that you first brought this

00:05:20.700 --> 00:05:21.280
idea to me.

00:05:21.280 --> 00:05:27.249
And I think I said, well, I
don't see any money in it.

00:05:27.249 --> 00:05:29.540
And not to be totally mercenary
about it, but it really

00:05:29.540 --> 00:05:31.370
was like, you know, to
really do this well,

00:05:31.370 --> 00:05:33.530
I think it's going
to require a lot.

00:05:33.530 --> 00:05:37.230
And for 2013, the key
to going down there

00:05:37.230 --> 00:05:40.190
was being able to make sure
that we weren't just doing

00:05:40.190 --> 00:05:42.840
this, paying for it
out of our own pockets,

00:05:42.840 --> 00:05:44.955
and having a go at it.

00:05:44.955 --> 00:05:46.330
We were not part
of the festival.

00:05:46.330 --> 00:05:48.134
We were doing this
kind of rogue.

00:05:48.134 --> 00:05:49.400
It was a rogue project.

00:05:49.400 --> 00:05:51.770
We got a condominium
on Riverside.

00:05:51.770 --> 00:05:54.300
We just set up, and we
invited people to come.

00:05:54.300 --> 00:05:58.070
And we kind of cobbled together
from some independent sources.

00:05:58.070 --> 00:06:01.410
You know, just people who would
advertise on the radio program

00:06:01.410 --> 00:06:04.000
would underwrite the
videos, would get, you know,

00:06:04.000 --> 00:06:06.310
placement within the videos
which sort of started us

00:06:06.310 --> 00:06:07.780
down that path.

00:06:07.780 --> 00:06:10.509
So being able to pay
for it-- and nobody lost

00:06:10.509 --> 00:06:12.300
any money on that--
and we were able to pay

00:06:12.300 --> 00:06:15.170
our artists a little bit
of money to participate,

00:06:15.170 --> 00:06:17.450
it sort of changed the
dynamic a little bit,

00:06:17.450 --> 00:06:19.480
and made it something
that we were all

00:06:19.480 --> 00:06:22.742
working towards in a different
way than just doing it for fun.

00:06:22.742 --> 00:06:24.450
BEN ARTHUR: And the
studios were awesome.

00:06:24.450 --> 00:06:26.075
ROB REINHART: The
songs were fantastic.

00:06:26.075 --> 00:06:26.807
Four of them.

00:06:26.807 --> 00:06:28.140
MATTHEW HENDERSHOT: Was it four?

00:06:28.140 --> 00:06:28.600
Or was it three?

00:06:28.600 --> 00:06:28.990
ROB REINHART: Four.

00:06:28.990 --> 00:06:30.430
MATTHEW HENDERSHOT: I want
to touch back on something.

00:06:30.430 --> 00:06:31.560
We got a condominium.

00:06:31.560 --> 00:06:32.839
You mentioned that.

00:06:32.839 --> 00:06:34.380
And Al, you went
down the first year.

00:06:34.380 --> 00:06:34.880
ALAN HOUGHTON: No, Mike.

00:06:34.880 --> 00:06:34.970
MATTHEW HENDERSHOT: Mike.

00:06:34.970 --> 00:06:37.220
Mike, you went down the
first year to do that.

00:06:37.220 --> 00:06:41.340
Talk about leaving, you know,
multimillion dollar Dubway

00:06:41.340 --> 00:06:43.230
Studio's facility and
going down to record

00:06:43.230 --> 00:06:44.230
these things in a condo.

00:06:44.230 --> 00:06:44.810
MICHAEL CREHORE:
You kind of have

00:06:44.810 --> 00:06:46.620
to think outside of
the box a little bit.

00:06:46.620 --> 00:06:49.740
And, but you know,
the whole world

00:06:49.740 --> 00:06:53.990
has, has come to this
gorilla recording thing

00:06:53.990 --> 00:06:54.820
and embraced it.

00:06:54.820 --> 00:06:57.050
I mean, just look at
YouTube and anything else.

00:06:57.050 --> 00:07:01.240
Everybody is both
recording, and taking video,

00:07:01.240 --> 00:07:02.480
and doing it themselves.

00:07:02.480 --> 00:07:05.290
And Al and I both
came-- even though we

00:07:05.290 --> 00:07:07.090
had a beautiful
studio to work in-- we

00:07:07.090 --> 00:07:09.130
came from a
do-it-yourself background.

00:07:09.130 --> 00:07:12.490
So early on, we were-- you know,
before they had computers--

00:07:12.490 --> 00:07:15.060
were working with 2-tracks,
and 4-tracks, and 8-tracks,

00:07:15.060 --> 00:07:18.760
and 16-tracks, whatever we
could afford to kind of get

00:07:18.760 --> 00:07:20.290
the process going.

00:07:20.290 --> 00:07:25.444
So for me, it was pretty
invigorating to go.

00:07:25.444 --> 00:07:28.870
Ben said, hey, let's go to South
by Southwest and do this thing.

00:07:28.870 --> 00:07:30.520
And I'm like, yeah, OK.

00:07:30.520 --> 00:07:33.150
So we took a couple of small
interfaces down with us.

00:07:33.150 --> 00:07:35.110
I think we had four inputs.

00:07:35.110 --> 00:07:38.197
We were working in a
condominium, which meant Ben,

00:07:38.197 --> 00:07:40.280
you have to get up now,
because the guys are going

00:07:40.280 --> 00:07:41.470
to be here in a half hour.

00:07:41.470 --> 00:07:43.770
And we've got to move your
bed out of the living room

00:07:43.770 --> 00:07:46.764
and put it into the
bedroom so we can work.

00:07:46.764 --> 00:07:49.390
And but it was nice.

00:07:49.390 --> 00:07:53.106
And everybody,
everybody who came was,

00:07:53.106 --> 00:07:56.202
were in it for the, for
getting the best song

00:07:56.202 --> 00:07:57.410
they could get in the moment.

00:07:57.410 --> 00:08:01.450
And when that happens,
it just makes the,

00:08:01.450 --> 00:08:02.526
makes the process easy.

00:08:02.526 --> 00:08:05.680
I mean, later on, we had to take
the things back to the studio

00:08:05.680 --> 00:08:08.160
and enhance some of
the productions a bit,

00:08:08.160 --> 00:08:09.480
which is also fun for me.

00:08:09.480 --> 00:08:12.216
Because I get to play a lot of
instruments and put on a lot

00:08:12.216 --> 00:08:12.840
different hats.

00:08:12.840 --> 00:08:15.130
But it was great.

00:08:15.130 --> 00:08:17.724
I mean, you just have
to capture that moment

00:08:17.724 --> 00:08:22.570
when Ben and this artist
get the kernel of a song.

00:08:22.570 --> 00:08:24.760
And I think Rob, that
first year he was saying,

00:08:24.760 --> 00:08:26.170
you know, he's he's, sweating.

00:08:26.170 --> 00:08:28.770
He's going, I don't know
if this is going to work.

00:08:28.770 --> 00:08:29.690
Does this really work?

00:08:29.690 --> 00:08:30.880
Is this really going to work?

00:08:30.880 --> 00:08:33.020
ROB REINHART: Something I
continue to do to this day.

00:08:33.020 --> 00:08:34.309
MICHAEL CREHORE:
And so go ahead.

00:08:34.309 --> 00:08:34.850
Tell them--

00:08:34.850 --> 00:08:36.230
ROB REINHART: Well, we should,
we should point out though,

00:08:36.230 --> 00:08:38.771
and we should just make it very
clear that what we were doing

00:08:38.771 --> 00:08:41.350
was trying to create a
brand new song-- brand

00:08:41.350 --> 00:08:44.579
new song-- from nothing in about
a three hour period of time

00:08:44.579 --> 00:08:45.370
with these artists.

00:08:45.370 --> 00:08:46.666
We didn't have them for long.

00:08:46.666 --> 00:08:48.040
We just had them
for a few hours.

00:08:48.040 --> 00:08:50.030
We were working in a
space that really was not

00:08:50.030 --> 00:08:51.307
much larger than this stage.

00:08:51.307 --> 00:08:52.890
MICHAEL CREHORE: No,
it was probably--

00:08:52.890 --> 00:08:54.100
ROB REINHART: You put
the kitchen there.

00:08:54.100 --> 00:08:54.660
That's it.

00:08:54.660 --> 00:08:57.100
This was the condo
we were working in.

00:08:57.100 --> 00:08:59.080
And everybody brought
different ideas.

00:08:59.080 --> 00:09:00.980
I mean, some brought
no ideas whatsoever.

00:09:00.980 --> 00:09:03.330
I mean, they really
just-- Ben and the artist

00:09:03.330 --> 00:09:06.030
staring at each
other for a second.

00:09:06.030 --> 00:09:06.850
Now we go.

00:09:06.850 --> 00:09:09.000
And we were capturing
it on video and audio,

00:09:09.000 --> 00:09:11.070
and yeah, it was a little scary.

00:09:11.070 --> 00:09:12.090
Sure.

00:09:12.090 --> 00:09:14.520
MATTHEW HENDERSHOT: Well, and
I think one of things for me

00:09:14.520 --> 00:09:17.880
on the video direction
standpoint that

00:09:17.880 --> 00:09:21.560
was important was always
telling the real story,

00:09:21.560 --> 00:09:25.150
and then focusing on
that creative moment.

00:09:25.150 --> 00:09:28.030
One of the things that we talk
about us as creative people

00:09:28.030 --> 00:09:29.490
is like demo-itis.

00:09:29.490 --> 00:09:31.250
Or that, you know,
when-- the first time

00:09:31.250 --> 00:09:32.980
you draw a picture, the
first time you do something,

00:09:32.980 --> 00:09:34.300
you're like, aw,
this is perfect.

00:09:34.300 --> 00:09:36.758
And then, the more you work on
it, the more you work on it,

00:09:36.758 --> 00:09:39.220
you get further and further
away from that initial charge.

00:09:39.220 --> 00:09:41.580
And I know that's a big
philosophy of yours, too, Mike,

00:09:41.580 --> 00:09:43.720
is like, catch it
in that first time.

00:09:43.720 --> 00:09:46.100
So I think that we really
embraced that, going down

00:09:46.100 --> 00:09:48.410
to say, this is the situation.

00:09:48.410 --> 00:09:50.060
This is the reality
of it all, right?

00:09:50.060 --> 00:09:53.710
BEN ARTHUR: Yeah, and the songs
aren't meant to be necessarily,

00:09:53.710 --> 00:09:58.120
like, you know, sometimes a
live song goes on an album,

00:09:58.120 --> 00:10:01.850
and some of the falling
apart is beautiful.

00:10:01.850 --> 00:10:08.710
But the mess, you know,
is really compelling.

00:10:08.710 --> 00:10:12.160
And the fear and the
excitement of trying

00:10:12.160 --> 00:10:17.410
to remember the lyrics and
trying to play it right

00:10:17.410 --> 00:10:21.290
is present, and adds,
heightens the song.

00:10:21.290 --> 00:10:23.410
So, you know, we've had
artists come on the show,

