00:37:01.440 --> 00:37:04.730
from the past what is
now six years of working

00:37:04.730 --> 00:37:08.030
on this project for some
of us, like what do you--

00:37:08.030 --> 00:37:08.780
what do you think?

00:37:12.770 --> 00:37:14.269
Stumped him with that.

00:37:14.269 --> 00:37:15.810
BEN ARTHUR: It's an
exciting project.

00:37:15.810 --> 00:37:16.320
It's fun.

00:37:16.320 --> 00:37:20.270
And I, you know, as
long as the process

00:37:20.270 --> 00:37:25.540
itself continues to be
as exciting, and weird,

00:37:25.540 --> 00:37:28.587
and frightening, as
this is, and as long

00:37:28.587 --> 00:37:30.045
as we continue--
I mean, it really,

00:37:30.045 --> 00:37:31.750
it comes down to the art, right?

00:37:31.750 --> 00:37:37.110
So if we do it, if we make a
cake-- to go back to the cake

00:37:37.110 --> 00:37:41.130
metaphor-- that people
take home and, you know,

00:37:41.130 --> 00:37:48.580
listen to cake listeningwise,
and it's rotten,

00:37:48.580 --> 00:37:49.850
then we failed.

00:37:49.850 --> 00:37:52.290
At heart, it's a fun challenge.

00:37:52.290 --> 00:37:54.970
But if the art itself
isn't the center,

00:37:54.970 --> 00:37:57.520
doesn't hold that center,
then it doesn't work.

00:37:57.520 --> 00:37:59.840
And it doesn't work, I
think, internally for us too.

00:37:59.840 --> 00:38:05.260
The art has to have a life,
and to lift up, and feel

00:38:05.260 --> 00:38:07.760
like, yeah, that's a good song.

00:38:07.760 --> 00:38:10.750
Beyond just the
time limit, I think

00:38:10.750 --> 00:38:13.190
as long as that
continues to hold true,

00:38:13.190 --> 00:38:15.070
we're going to keep doing it.

00:38:15.070 --> 00:38:17.930
ALAN HOUGHTON: Yeah, it's
an interesting-- it was not

00:38:17.930 --> 00:38:21.960
a quandary, but it was an issue
to confront early on, given

00:38:21.960 --> 00:38:25.180
all the reality TV
that's out there,

00:38:25.180 --> 00:38:30.080
is you do have this tense
situation that can, you know,

00:38:30.080 --> 00:38:31.420
it can go south.

00:38:31.420 --> 00:38:34.290
With throwing in the
wrong flavors when--

00:38:34.290 --> 00:38:35.571
BEN ARTHUR: --of the cake.

00:38:35.571 --> 00:38:37.120
ALAN HOUGHTON: Of the cake, yes.

00:38:37.120 --> 00:38:38.050
ROB REINHART: The song cake.

00:38:38.050 --> 00:38:40.008
BEN ARTHUR: I never should
have mentioned cake.

00:38:40.008 --> 00:38:42.674
ALAN HOUGHTON: Yeah, the
artists can not get it together,

00:38:42.674 --> 00:38:43.840
some of them can have a fit.

00:38:43.840 --> 00:38:47.270
You can, it doesn't take
much to blow that vibe.

00:38:47.270 --> 00:38:50.864
And a TV producer
could even argue,

00:38:50.864 --> 00:38:52.780
you know, yeah, let's
screw it up a little bit

00:38:52.780 --> 00:38:55.300
and have some drama, and who
cares if the song-- you know,

00:38:55.300 --> 00:38:57.301
if the artist storms out
the door, that's great.

00:38:57.301 --> 00:38:58.550
That's what we're looking for.

00:38:58.550 --> 00:38:59.480
That's perfect.

00:38:59.480 --> 00:39:03.340
But we, you know, we made a
conscious decision, that's

00:39:03.340 --> 00:39:04.819
not what we're going to do.

00:39:04.819 --> 00:39:07.110
We are actually going to end
up with a really good song

00:39:07.110 --> 00:39:07.840
at the end.

00:39:07.840 --> 00:39:09.760
And one of the
things that's really

00:39:09.760 --> 00:39:12.399
heartening about the show--
and it's a surprise to me,

00:39:12.399 --> 00:39:13.940
and probably everybody
a little bit--

00:39:13.940 --> 00:39:16.860
is given all the
random elements,

00:39:16.860 --> 00:39:18.620
and everything that
goes into this,

00:39:18.620 --> 00:39:22.929
is how resourceful people are.

00:39:22.929 --> 00:39:24.220
We're not a big team, you know.

00:39:24.220 --> 00:39:25.800
And we pull off
a show like this.

00:39:25.800 --> 00:39:28.980
But also the artists
who are featured

00:39:28.980 --> 00:39:31.730
bring everything to bear in
a super short amount of time

00:39:31.730 --> 00:39:35.330
and create what've been
really great songs.

00:39:35.330 --> 00:39:36.507
It's probably startling.

00:39:36.507 --> 00:39:38.131
MICHAEL CREHORE: Rob
and I were talking

00:39:38.131 --> 00:39:39.640
about that the other day.

00:39:39.640 --> 00:39:42.790
Because we-- for this
talk we kind of went back

00:39:42.790 --> 00:39:46.220
through the archives and
Matthew had mentioned,

00:39:46.220 --> 00:39:48.410
do we have all the
music in one place?

00:39:48.410 --> 00:39:50.981
And I said, oh yeah, we
should, we should do that.

00:39:50.981 --> 00:39:52.480
So I put all the
music in one place.

00:39:52.480 --> 00:39:54.670
And, you know, we've
got about 20 songs now

00:39:54.670 --> 00:39:58.480
that we've written over
the past few years.

00:39:58.480 --> 00:40:03.150
And they all hold up as--
individually and collectively--

00:40:03.150 --> 00:40:09.860
as really nice songs
and it's enjoyable.

00:40:09.860 --> 00:40:11.730
ROB REINHART:
Acoustic Cafe-- this

00:40:11.730 --> 00:40:13.560
is what that program is about.

00:40:13.560 --> 00:40:15.340
It's about song craft.

00:40:15.340 --> 00:40:18.160
Not this song craft,
but it's about the craft

00:40:18.160 --> 00:40:19.530
of making songs.

00:40:19.530 --> 00:40:20.780
So I listen to a lot of songs.

00:40:20.780 --> 00:40:23.190
So 21 years down
the road, what I

00:40:23.190 --> 00:40:26.520
can say about this project
which has been so gratifying

00:40:26.520 --> 00:40:29.170
is that there is no template.

00:40:29.170 --> 00:40:31.500
Every one of these
situations is different.

00:40:31.500 --> 00:40:36.440
I kept thinking that
we'd get into a pattern.

00:40:36.440 --> 00:40:38.860
And the pattern, we would then
go and execute the pattern.

00:40:38.860 --> 00:40:41.970
What's great, what's
refreshing, what's fun

00:40:41.970 --> 00:40:43.780
is that there is no pattern.

00:40:43.780 --> 00:40:45.810
Every one of these,
I think everyone's

00:40:45.810 --> 00:40:48.600
about to become a
spectacular failure.

00:40:48.600 --> 00:40:49.880
BEN ARTHUR: It is.

00:40:49.880 --> 00:40:51.170
It absolutely is.

00:40:51.170 --> 00:40:52.830
ROB REINHART: And
then it's awesome.

00:40:52.830 --> 00:40:53.700
And it's great.

00:40:53.700 --> 00:40:55.527
One of, one of
these days it may.

00:40:55.527 --> 00:40:57.610
BEN ARTHUR: I thought, I
would have put money down

00:40:57.610 --> 00:40:59.734
that we would have crashed
into a wall before this.

00:40:59.734 --> 00:41:01.070
I absolutely would have.

00:41:01.070 --> 00:41:02.986
ROB REINHART: And this
new one, you know what?

00:41:02.986 --> 00:41:04.670
I am, so every one,
I'm just thrilled

00:41:04.670 --> 00:41:06.870
to get to the next
one, to be able to do

00:41:06.870 --> 00:41:08.964
the segment for
the radio program,

00:41:08.964 --> 00:41:11.460
put it out there on the 100
affiliates that we have,

00:41:11.460 --> 00:41:14.060
and get it heard in the world.

00:41:14.060 --> 00:41:15.860
This new one, I can't wait.

00:41:15.860 --> 00:41:16.890
December 7.

00:41:16.890 --> 00:41:17.890
MATTHEW HENDERSHOT: Yup.

00:41:17.890 --> 00:41:21.760
December 7 the last episode of
this year's Songs of the Road

00:41:21.760 --> 00:41:23.060
will to air.

00:41:23.060 --> 00:41:24.560
It publishes on YouTube.

00:41:24.560 --> 00:41:28.270
We use the YouTube network
to publish these things,

00:41:28.270 --> 00:41:30.970
and to share them out, and
to make them available.

00:41:30.970 --> 00:41:33.040
And I can say,
from my standpoint

00:41:33.040 --> 00:41:35.970
as the director and
editor of these things

00:41:35.970 --> 00:41:39.040
to put it together, it's always
been very important to me

00:41:39.040 --> 00:41:40.770
to be honest in
our storytelling,

00:41:40.770 --> 00:41:45.590
and to show you what is more
a documentary of the story

00:41:45.590 --> 00:41:48.180
unfolding, rather than
to try to manhandle,

00:41:48.180 --> 00:41:51.180
and manipulate, and go
that route of reality TV.

00:41:51.180 --> 00:41:53.780
I think a lot of
those shows, they

00:41:53.780 --> 00:41:56.550
focus-- even on, not even one
when it's the task at hand.

00:41:56.550 --> 00:41:59.100
You know, they want the
bickering, and the argument

00:41:59.100 --> 00:42:01.310
on the side, and
whatever the show's about

00:42:01.310 --> 00:42:03.180
is actually only
a couple minutes.

00:42:03.180 --> 00:42:08.970
And instead, we've tried to
put forward an honest telling

00:42:08.970 --> 00:42:10.600
of hey, this is what went down.

00:42:10.600 --> 00:42:13.207
And I think it shows
a glimpse into a world

00:42:13.207 --> 00:42:14.790
that a lot of people
don't get to see.

00:42:14.790 --> 00:42:16.498
Unless you're in that
room, unless you're

00:42:16.498 --> 00:42:18.990
one of the people writing
that song, in a normal world

00:42:18.990 --> 00:42:20.470
you would never get access.

00:42:20.470 --> 00:42:23.260
BEN ARTHUR: Yeah, and that's
a funny thing about artists

00:42:23.260 --> 00:42:26.800
is that I think a
lot of us really

00:42:26.800 --> 00:42:32.051
love that creative thing that
is largely a private affair,

00:42:32.051 --> 00:42:32.550
you know?

00:42:32.550 --> 00:42:36.600
Like, except for opportunities
like this, for the most part

00:42:36.600 --> 00:42:37.605
it's done away.

00:42:37.605 --> 00:42:39.980
But it's one of the things
that I get a huge kick out of,

00:42:39.980 --> 00:42:42.760
and I think a lot of artists
get a huge kick out of.

00:42:42.760 --> 00:42:45.240
And sort of opening
up the window on that,

00:42:45.240 --> 00:42:48.500
and sharing that
true fear and joy

00:42:48.500 --> 00:42:50.250
is one of the great
pleasures of the show.

00:42:50.250 --> 00:42:51.791
MATTHEW HENDERSHOT:
Well, and there's

00:42:51.791 --> 00:42:54.000
a lot of stuff to be learned,
I think, about it too.

00:42:54.000 --> 00:42:57.122
No artists have
worked the same way.

00:42:57.122 --> 00:42:58.330
Some want to do lyrics first.

00:42:58.330 --> 00:42:59.610
Some want to do music first.

00:42:59.610 --> 00:43:02.120
And then, we haven't ever
really recorded it the same way.

00:43:02.120 --> 00:43:03.971
So even if you're into
that stuff, you can--

00:43:03.971 --> 00:43:05.470
ROB REINHART: Yeah,
every single one

00:43:05.470 --> 00:43:08.530
has been completely different.

00:43:08.530 --> 00:43:10.742
MATTHEW HENDERSHOT: So we
will give you a sneak peak

00:43:10.742 --> 00:43:12.290
of this last little clip.

00:43:12.290 --> 00:43:15.460
This features a very
talented artist.

00:43:15.460 --> 00:43:18.990
My Brightest Diamond, Shara
Worden, who is from Detroit.

00:43:18.990 --> 00:43:20.530
And we went to Detroit to do it.

00:43:20.530 --> 00:43:22.244
And it was quite an event.

00:43:22.244 --> 00:43:23.910
BEN ARTHUR: Yeah, and
a brand new style.

00:43:23.910 --> 00:43:28.450
She wanted to write something
and have a DJ manipulate

00:43:28.450 --> 00:43:31.860
the pieces and
then sort of start

00:43:31.860 --> 00:43:34.650
from that thing which
she hadn't yet heard,

00:43:34.650 --> 00:43:37.320
which we had never tried before,
and we'd never worked with a DJ

00:43:37.320 --> 00:43:38.440
before.

00:43:38.440 --> 00:43:42.560
And she also wanted a
horn section, so it was.

00:43:42.560 --> 00:43:44.210
MATTHEW HENDERSHOT:
Upping the ante.

00:43:44.210 --> 00:43:47.204
Here's a little tease
of the upcoming episode.

00:43:47.204 --> 00:43:48.009
[VIDEO PLAYBACK]

00:43:48.009 --> 00:43:50.300
-Raise your hand if you're
ready to go perform it live.

00:43:54.580 --> 00:43:56.544
The show, The Eastern
Market is leaving.

00:43:56.544 --> 00:43:57.043
All right.

00:43:57.043 --> 00:43:57.970
Who's driving it?

00:43:57.970 --> 00:43:58.510
-Have fun.

00:43:58.510 --> 00:44:00.370
Listen, I'll go.

00:44:00.370 --> 00:44:01.150
-OK.

00:44:01.150 --> 00:44:03.270
I personally feel like
the live performance

00:44:03.270 --> 00:44:04.950
is going to be great.

00:44:04.950 --> 00:44:07.750
-Wiz is going to do this
all live and take that risk

00:44:07.750 --> 00:44:10.450
because that brings her to
a new level of performance.

00:44:10.450 --> 00:44:15.640
-The most important thing
for me in a live experience

00:44:15.640 --> 00:44:19.600
is feeling, feeling,
feeling, feeling, feeling.

00:44:19.600 --> 00:44:21.510
It's a really hard part to sing.

00:44:21.510 --> 00:44:24.380
And I've never sang without
a guitar in front of me.

00:44:24.380 --> 00:44:26.610
I may actually just
hold it in front of me

00:44:26.610 --> 00:44:27.910
like a security blanket.

00:44:27.910 --> 00:44:29.580
And I've never sang
anything this high.

00:44:33.029 --> 00:44:34.570
We've never had an
audience this big.

00:44:34.570 --> 00:44:37.216
And it's Rob's hometown.

00:44:37.216 --> 00:44:40.105
And it's yeah, some pressure.

00:44:40.105 --> 00:44:42.230
-The performance is going
to be the very first time

00:44:42.230 --> 00:44:45.450
that all six of us
are playing this song.

00:44:45.450 --> 00:44:49.000
Together, first time,
in front of people.

00:44:49.000 --> 00:44:51.322
We are definitely
working without a net.

00:44:54.214 --> 00:44:54.798
[END PLAYBACK]

00:44:54.798 --> 00:44:56.630
MATTHEW HENDERSHOT: So
I encourage you guys.

00:44:56.630 --> 00:44:59.185
December 7 that'll be available
on our YouTube channel, Song

00:44:59.185 --> 00:45:00.300
Craft Presents.

00:45:00.300 --> 00:45:03.045
And guys, anything you want
to say before we open up

00:45:03.045 --> 00:45:04.460
for questions?

00:45:04.460 --> 00:45:06.126
ROB REINHART: Thank
you for taking time.

00:45:06.126 --> 00:45:08.185
BEN ARTHUR: Yeah,
thanks for having us.

00:45:08.185 --> 00:45:10.560
MATTHEW HENDERSHOT: Happily,
if anyone has any questions?

00:45:10.560 --> 00:45:10.960
AUDIENCE: Hi, guys.

00:45:10.960 --> 00:45:11.500
I'm Lauren.

00:45:11.500 --> 00:45:12.690
Thank you for coming.

00:45:12.690 --> 00:45:14.232
I love your project.

00:45:14.232 --> 00:45:15.190
I had a quick question.

00:45:15.190 --> 00:45:18.864
I wondered how'd you guys find
your talent and the artist

00:45:18.864 --> 00:45:19.780
in each of the cities?

00:45:22.960 --> 00:45:27.150
ROB REINHART: Well, we
sort of crafted lists.

00:45:27.150 --> 00:45:30.270
I mean, I'm sort of,
for the radio program,

00:45:30.270 --> 00:45:32.870
I'm in touch with a
lot of just people.

00:45:32.870 --> 00:45:35.350
And when we knew we were going
to be in a particular place,

00:45:35.350 --> 00:45:38.530
they weren't necessarily
artists from that city.

00:45:38.530 --> 00:45:41.290
In a couple of cases,
we had that happen.

00:45:41.290 --> 00:45:43.580
And then, in others,
you know, people

00:45:43.580 --> 00:45:45.440
were just going to be
at South by Southwest.

00:45:45.440 --> 00:45:49.080
And if they were going to be
there, we would bring them,

00:45:49.080 --> 00:45:50.800
you know, we would
extend the invitation.

00:45:50.800 --> 00:45:53.470
A lot of artists--
you know, the key

00:45:53.470 --> 00:45:57.346
was finding an artist where this
project would work for them.

00:45:57.346 --> 00:45:58.720
We had a lot of
artists who said,

00:45:58.720 --> 00:46:00.178
boy, that sounds
like a lot of fun,

00:46:00.178 --> 00:46:02.330
but I would be
terrified to do that.

00:46:02.330 --> 00:46:03.210
I can't do it.

00:46:03.210 --> 00:46:05.820
So a lot of people
just turned us down.

00:46:05.820 --> 00:46:09.260
BEN ARTHUR: Aesop Rock-- Aesop
Rock is a friend of Wiz's-- DJ

00:46:09.260 --> 00:46:12.000
Wiz-- and I asked
him to ask Ace.

00:46:12.000 --> 00:46:14.150
And Ace emailed
back and was like,

00:46:14.150 --> 00:46:17.101
I would never stop throwing up.

00:46:17.101 --> 00:46:19.114
So it's out of the question.

00:46:19.114 --> 00:46:20.780
MICHAEL CREHORE: And
one of our artists,

00:46:20.780 --> 00:46:23.740
David Mayfield, who
was he was Nashville

00:46:23.740 --> 00:46:28.540
based for a long time, he's
now back in his native Ohio.

00:46:28.540 --> 00:46:31.544
We actually recorded
him in Los Angeles.

00:46:31.544 --> 00:46:33.960
So we had-- it was a different
kind of a road experience--

00:46:33.960 --> 00:46:38.580
but the interesting thing was
we rented an Airbnb which turned

00:46:38.580 --> 00:46:40.056
out to be Roger Miller's house.

00:46:40.056 --> 00:46:41.680
And Roger Miller
wrote King of the Road

00:46:41.680 --> 00:46:44.110
and a bunch of other great hits.

00:46:44.110 --> 00:46:47.959
And Roger Miller, as I'm driving
around with David Mayfield,

00:46:47.959 --> 00:46:50.250
I said, you know, we're
staying at Roger Miller's house

00:46:50.250 --> 00:46:50.750
tonight?

00:46:50.750 --> 00:46:52.880
And he just, he
completely broke down.

00:46:52.880 --> 00:46:55.550
Roger Miller was
his boyhood hero,

00:46:55.550 --> 00:46:58.170
as a singer,
songwriter, entertainer.

00:46:58.170 --> 00:47:01.940
And so it was just this
weird confluence of events

00:47:01.940 --> 00:47:03.840
that we were staying in
Roger Miller's house,

00:47:03.840 --> 00:47:06.380
we're going to be working
in Roger Miller's house

00:47:06.380 --> 00:47:07.500
ROB REINHART: With
an artist from Ohio.

00:47:07.500 --> 00:47:09.250
MICHAEL CREHORE: With
an artist from Ohio,

00:47:09.250 --> 00:47:10.180
who that was his hero.

00:47:10.180 --> 00:47:12.290
So it's kind of an
interesting thing.

00:47:12.290 --> 00:47:15.640
BEN ARTHUR: To get, to
drill in a little more.

00:47:15.640 --> 00:47:18.140
Rob's show-- he doesn't
mention this often.

00:47:18.140 --> 00:47:20.140
But Rob's show airs for
something like 2 and 1/2

00:47:20.140 --> 00:47:21.500
million people a week.

00:47:21.500 --> 00:47:24.430
So he gets pitched
every artist who

00:47:24.430 --> 00:47:30.340
has music within the range
of stuff Acoustic Cafe plays.

00:47:30.340 --> 00:47:35.620
So he's, you know, very
in touch with what's

00:47:35.620 --> 00:47:36.650
out there in the world.

00:47:36.650 --> 00:47:41.400
And so that, plus all of
our collective fandoms

00:47:41.400 --> 00:47:44.730
of various people,
and I think all of us

00:47:44.730 --> 00:47:47.300
have at various points pitched
people that we were just like,

00:47:47.300 --> 00:47:49.050
oh, man, I love her.

00:47:49.050 --> 00:47:49.870
She's amazing.

00:47:49.870 --> 00:47:51.240
We need to get her on the show.

00:47:51.240 --> 00:47:53.149
And sometimes it
works scheduling-wise,

00:47:53.149 --> 00:47:54.190
and sometimes it doesn't.

00:47:54.190 --> 00:47:57.940
Sometimes it works as far as
the fear-- vomiting-- factor.

00:47:57.940 --> 00:47:59.110
And sometimes it doesn't.

00:47:59.110 --> 00:48:00.834
But every once in
awhile, we get,

00:48:00.834 --> 00:48:02.250
you know, the
people that we want.

00:48:02.250 --> 00:48:04.100
And it's a real thrill.

00:48:04.100 --> 00:48:07.060
ROB REINHART: And we also
wanted to allow the artist

00:48:07.060 --> 00:48:10.620
to help to, you know,
design the trip.

00:48:10.620 --> 00:48:14.360
So, what would inspire you
to create something great?

00:48:14.360 --> 00:48:16.929
So with Lera Lynn, she's
like, well-- you know,

00:48:16.929 --> 00:48:19.470
you know, within a three hour
road trip, that kind of thing--

00:48:19.470 --> 00:48:20.890
she said, well, why
don't we go to Memphis?

00:48:20.890 --> 00:48:23.310
And then, the whole thought
of going to Sun Studios

00:48:23.310 --> 00:48:26.600
was a real thrill for her.

00:48:26.600 --> 00:48:28.470
Yeah, I mean, so, you
know, we wanted people

00:48:28.470 --> 00:48:30.610
to-- Shara Worden,
obviously she wanted

00:48:30.610 --> 00:48:34.380
to do kind of a love letter
to Detroit in Detroit.

00:48:34.380 --> 00:48:35.710
We opened it up to her.

00:48:35.710 --> 00:48:37.680
We said, we can go
anywhere you want to go.

00:48:37.680 --> 00:48:38.980
And she said, I want
to stay in Detroit.

00:48:38.980 --> 00:48:39.896
I want to do it there.

00:48:39.896 --> 00:48:42.440
So that was another
part that went

00:48:42.440 --> 00:48:44.180
into the selection,
where they wanted,

00:48:44.180 --> 00:48:45.776
what would inspire
them the most.

00:48:45.776 --> 00:48:47.650
MATTHEW HENDERSHOT:
Thanks for your question.

00:48:47.650 --> 00:48:49.610
BEN ARTHUR: Thanks.

00:48:49.610 --> 00:48:52.790
MATTHEW HENDERSHOT: Any
additional questions?

00:48:52.790 --> 00:48:54.020
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:48:54.020 --> 00:48:56.200
Yeah, I've got lots of
questions, but I guess

00:48:56.200 --> 00:48:56.860
BEN ARTHUR: Hit us
with all of them.

00:48:56.860 --> 00:48:57.693
We'll take them all.

00:48:57.693 --> 00:48:59.810
AUDIENCE: The one that
I'm kind of curious

00:48:59.810 --> 00:49:03.810
about it is just about
those choking points,

00:49:03.810 --> 00:49:06.140
when people like
just realize I don't

00:49:06.140 --> 00:49:08.430
think we can do this in
time, or anything like that.

00:49:08.430 --> 00:49:13.510
Have you actually had to extend
the clock for people in order

00:49:13.510 --> 00:49:14.700
to get something done?

00:49:14.700 --> 00:49:15.659
BEN ARTHUR: Not really.

00:49:15.659 --> 00:49:16.950
MATTHEW HENDERSHOT: It's funny.

00:49:16.950 --> 00:49:19.180
We've actually had to turn
the screws on bringing

00:49:19.180 --> 00:49:21.040
certain things to a close.

00:49:21.040 --> 00:49:25.290
With the sneak peek
episode-- the new one that

00:49:25.290 --> 00:49:27.670
will come out-- there
was a point where

00:49:27.670 --> 00:49:30.190
I was kind of running around
the studios we're recording

00:49:30.190 --> 00:49:31.930
in saying, guys, it's time.

00:49:31.930 --> 00:49:32.430
We gotta go.

00:49:32.430 --> 00:49:32.930
We gotta go.

00:49:32.930 --> 00:49:33.790
We gotta go.

00:49:33.790 --> 00:49:36.984
And they still wanted
to do more vocal takes.

00:49:36.984 --> 00:49:38.400
You saw them sitting
in the booth.

00:49:38.400 --> 00:49:39.740
BEN ARTHUR: I was trying.

00:49:39.740 --> 00:49:42.130
So, you know, what
usually happens

00:49:42.130 --> 00:49:45.300
is we talk to an artist,
and they're like, well,

00:49:45.300 --> 00:49:47.992
how long would I need to,
you know, maybe the manager,

00:49:47.992 --> 00:49:49.950
how long would the artist
need to be available?

00:49:49.950 --> 00:49:52.960
We can only give you
three hours, or whatever.

00:49:52.960 --> 00:49:59.210
We say now that we've learned,
we'll ask of you three hours.

00:49:59.210 --> 00:50:02.050
But give us an extra
two hours on the end

00:50:02.050 --> 00:50:05.110
because your artist will want
to spend more time doing this.

00:50:05.110 --> 00:50:09.100
Your artist will not be happy
with, you know, the bridge,

00:50:09.100 --> 00:50:10.202
or with the vocal.

00:50:10.202 --> 00:50:11.660
And they will want
to keep playing.

00:50:11.660 --> 00:50:13.950
Because really it's
genuinely a joy.

00:50:13.950 --> 00:50:16.540
AUDIENCE: Is it mostly-- is
the time extension mostly then

00:50:16.540 --> 00:50:18.460
for sort of
production type stuff?

00:50:18.460 --> 00:50:21.130
Like at that point, you've
got lyrics, and melody,

00:50:21.130 --> 00:50:22.540
and all that stuff down?

00:50:22.540 --> 00:50:23.870
MATTHEW HENDERSHOT: Yeah,
I think that's fair.

00:50:23.870 --> 00:50:25.578
MICHAEL CREHORE: I
don't think we've ever

00:50:25.578 --> 00:50:29.130
come up to the end of the
clock and not had the song.

00:50:29.130 --> 00:50:32.950
The song seems to come together,
and I think most of that

00:50:32.950 --> 00:50:33.760
has to do with Ben.

00:50:33.760 --> 00:50:36.070
Bend is a really
great facilitator

00:50:36.070 --> 00:50:37.660
in the songwriting process.

00:50:37.660 --> 00:50:38.875
BEN ARTHUR: Thanks.

00:50:38.875 --> 00:50:40.166
MICHAEL CREHORE: And it's true.

00:50:40.166 --> 00:50:44.360
He'll, he'll, you know,
whatever they're going through,

00:50:44.360 --> 00:50:46.160
you know, it'll get to a point.

00:50:46.160 --> 00:50:48.990
And he'll bring it to a close.

00:50:48.990 --> 00:50:50.862
Sometimes he's used
the process of,

00:50:50.862 --> 00:50:52.070
let's go into separate rooms.

00:50:52.070 --> 00:50:52.820
You bring a verse.

00:50:52.820 --> 00:50:53.710
I'll bring a verse.

00:50:53.710 --> 00:50:56.632
And sometimes they just
hit it off right away.

00:50:56.632 --> 00:50:58.090
BEN ARTHUR: It's
actually something

00:50:58.090 --> 00:51:02.890
that-- Matthew's encouraged
me to slow down a little bit.

00:51:02.890 --> 00:51:07.770
Because the fear gets into me
too, even after all this time.

00:51:07.770 --> 00:51:11.920
And I'll push into
territory that, you know,

00:51:11.920 --> 00:51:14.780
maybe if I gave a little
more space the artist,

00:51:14.780 --> 00:51:17.280
they'd-- you know, because
you see the sort of blank

00:51:17.280 --> 00:51:18.340
expression.

00:51:18.340 --> 00:51:22.540
And so I will, out of
empathy, if nothing else,

00:51:22.540 --> 00:51:23.730
try to rush in.

00:51:23.730 --> 00:51:26.260
And Matthew has been
very good about reminding

00:51:26.260 --> 00:51:29.330
me to, you know, like
a good psychoanalyst,

00:51:29.330 --> 00:51:31.140
let it hang a little bit.

00:51:31.140 --> 00:51:35.720
And see if that space, they'll
come in and fill that space.

00:51:35.720 --> 00:51:40.210
So the creatively, almost
never that I recall,

00:51:40.210 --> 00:51:45.000
Ben Sollee and Erin McKeown took
a little bit longer than some.

00:51:45.000 --> 00:51:46.910
But usually it's a production.

00:51:46.910 --> 00:51:48.440
The artist wants
to keep polishing.

00:51:48.440 --> 00:51:49.100
AUDIENCE: Of course.

00:51:49.100 --> 00:51:50.010
I could see where
that would be--

00:51:50.010 --> 00:51:52.259
MICHAEL CREHORE: The thing
that important for Al and I

00:51:52.259 --> 00:51:55.590
is, I think, is to get a
performance of the vocal.

00:51:55.590 --> 00:51:58.120
Because at the end of
the day, we may not--

00:51:58.120 --> 00:52:01.800
you know, if we get
that lead performance,

00:52:01.800 --> 00:52:03.880
one that we know
we can work with.

00:52:03.880 --> 00:52:07.610
We're not big proponents of
tuning, and moving things

00:52:07.610 --> 00:52:09.290
around, and making
everything perfect.

00:52:09.290 --> 00:52:10.882
We're a little more old school.

00:52:10.882 --> 00:52:13.090
So we want to make sure that
performance is something

00:52:13.090 --> 00:52:14.760
that we can then
build a track around.

00:52:14.760 --> 00:52:17.780
And in some cases, we
worked with A.J. Croce

00:52:17.780 --> 00:52:21.030
down in the South by Southwest.

00:52:21.030 --> 00:52:23.220
And we really couldn't
do anything to his track.

00:52:23.220 --> 00:52:23.510
BEN ARTHUR: He asked us to.

00:52:23.510 --> 00:52:25.468
MICHAEL CREHORE: It was
such a beautiful, yeah,

00:52:25.468 --> 00:52:27.810
it was such a beautiful
performance of the vocal,

00:52:27.810 --> 00:52:30.050
and the guitar--
acoustic guitar--

00:52:30.050 --> 00:52:32.070
that we didn't
want to produce it.

00:52:32.070 --> 00:52:34.761
We started to produce it,
and we went, you know what?

00:52:34.761 --> 00:52:35.260
This is

00:52:35.260 --> 00:52:37.100
AUDIENCE: That was the one
we saw initially there?

00:52:37.100 --> 00:52:37.820
BEN ARTHUR: No.

00:52:37.820 --> 00:52:39.420
MATTHEW HENDERSHOT: No
you'll have to go online

00:52:39.420 --> 00:52:41.170
MICHAEL CREHORE: --to
go online to see it.

00:52:41.170 --> 00:52:44.720
But it's just a really, you
know, that was all it needed.

00:52:44.720 --> 00:52:46.907
And for some of the
others, we produced them.

00:52:46.907 --> 00:52:49.240
Brought them up a little bit
with either drums, or bass,

00:52:49.240 --> 00:52:51.190
or some extra guitars,
or some keyboards,

00:52:51.190 --> 00:52:54.565
but it's just really getting
that vocal, you know?

00:52:54.565 --> 00:52:56.190
ALAN HOUGHTON: Yeah,
and to your point,

00:52:56.190 --> 00:52:59.600
these songwriters
are professional.

00:52:59.600 --> 00:53:00.370
You know?

00:53:00.370 --> 00:53:02.560
If you say, you know, 3
o'clock, we have to go.

00:53:02.560 --> 00:53:03.490
Because we have
to be at the place

00:53:03.490 --> 00:53:05.698
where you're actually going
to sing the song in front

00:53:05.698 --> 00:53:07.960
of 40 people, you know,
they don't ignore that.

00:53:07.960 --> 00:53:08.550
You know.

00:53:08.550 --> 00:53:11.090
So everyone's working
to make it happen.

00:53:11.090 --> 00:53:13.420
And maybe, yeah, it'd great
to have 15 extra minutes,

00:53:13.420 --> 00:53:14.540
but sometimes you don't.

00:53:14.540 --> 00:53:15.040
You know?

00:53:15.040 --> 00:53:16.622
And you just go
with what you got.

00:53:16.622 --> 00:53:18.830
MATTHEW HENDERSHOT: Also
from a technical standpoint,

00:53:18.830 --> 00:53:21.524
and I think this applies
a bit to Mike and Al

00:53:21.524 --> 00:53:22.940
as well, but
definitely from where

00:53:22.940 --> 00:53:25.040
I'm coming from
from the video side,

00:53:25.040 --> 00:53:27.580
is that we're essentially
there to document.

00:53:27.580 --> 00:53:30.855
So we definitely don't
want to be pushing it

00:53:30.855 --> 00:53:33.180
in any certain way to
try and-- because then we

00:53:33.180 --> 00:53:36.085
fall into that, just like
any other reality TV show,

00:53:36.085 --> 00:53:38.210
and we're not telling you
the honest story anymore.

00:53:38.210 --> 00:53:40.135
So one of the mottos
on the set all the time

00:53:40.135 --> 00:53:41.210
is, default to reality.

00:53:41.210 --> 00:53:42.340
What's really going on?

00:53:42.340 --> 00:53:43.730
What can we really do?

00:53:43.730 --> 00:53:45.980
And any times when we've
come to the wire, where we've

00:53:45.980 --> 00:53:48.360
had to be like, we don't
have any more time,

00:53:48.360 --> 00:53:51.380
it's because the live
performance is scheduled.

00:53:51.380 --> 00:53:54.000
And people, the audience
is starting to show up.

00:53:54.000 --> 00:53:56.390
And they're like, well,
are they going to show up?

00:53:56.390 --> 00:53:57.473
Are they going to perform?

00:53:57.473 --> 00:54:01.050
So a lot of that is reality
setting that timeline versus us

00:54:01.050 --> 00:54:03.931
trying to manipulate the story.

00:54:03.931 --> 00:54:06.430
And I think that's true a little
bit with the songs as well.

00:54:06.430 --> 00:54:09.254
You guys are just documenting
those beautiful moments,

00:54:09.254 --> 00:54:11.170
and then, you know,
touching it where you can.

00:54:11.170 --> 00:54:13.086
MICHAEL CREHORE: Yeah,
we're not-- we're not--

00:54:13.086 --> 00:54:14.960
very light-handed production.

00:54:14.960 --> 00:54:17.070
BEN ARTHUR: And as per
the artist's instruction.

00:54:17.070 --> 00:54:19.550
Essentially, at the end of
a recording session, we say,

00:54:19.550 --> 00:54:23.520
is there anything you
want us to augment or add?

00:54:23.520 --> 00:54:26.140
And then, depending
on what they want,

00:54:26.140 --> 00:54:28.560
we'll do that, send it to
them, and say, this is right?

00:54:28.560 --> 00:54:31.250
And sometimes it is,
sometimes it isn't.

00:54:31.250 --> 00:54:32.850
And then, and then, move on.

00:54:32.850 --> 00:54:33.820
Because at the end
of the day, we're

00:54:33.820 --> 00:54:35.090
serving that artist's vision.

00:54:35.090 --> 00:54:36.980
And if the song doesn't
sound like the artist

00:54:36.980 --> 00:54:39.020
and doesn't sound natural,
like that's not going

00:54:39.020 --> 00:54:41.460
to be good for us or them.

00:54:41.460 --> 00:54:44.364
AUDIENCE: Well, thanks, you
answered a lot of questions.

00:54:44.364 --> 00:54:45.780
ROB REINHART: Thank
you very much.

